## Project Structure

```
llm-os-shell/
├── src/
│   └── llm_os_shell/
│       ├── __init__.py        # Version and package metadata
│       ├── __main__.py        # python -m llm_os_shell entry point
│       ├── cli.py             # Argument parser and CLI entry
│       ├── shell.py           # Main interactive shell loop
│       ├── risk.py            # Risk classification engine (50+ patterns)
│       ├── llm_backend.py     # Pluggable LLM backend abstraction
│       ├── executor.py        # Command executor (builtins + subprocess)
│       ├── display.py         # Terminal display and color output
│       ├── logger.py          # Structured JSON-L interaction logger
│       └── config.py          # Config loading (env vars + TOML file)
├── tests/
│   ├── test_risk.py           # Risk engine tests
│   ├── test_llm_backend.py    # Backend tests (with mocking)
│   ├── test_executor.py       # Execution tests
│   ├── test_config.py         # Config tests
│   ├── test_shell.py          # Shell integration tests
│   └── test_logger.py         # Logger tests
├── examples/
│   ├── dangerous_commands.sh  # Annotated examples of LLM handling
│   └── config_example.toml   # Full configuration reference
├── .github/
│   └── workflows/ci.yml       # GitHub Actions CI
├── pyproject.toml             # Package metadata and build config
├── LICENSE                    # MIT License
└── README.md
```

---

## Supported Models (via Ollama)

Any model that can produce structured JSON output works well. Recommended:

| Model | Pull command | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| Llama 3 8B | `ollama pull llama3` | Best balance of speed and quality |
| Mistral 7B | `ollama pull mistral` | Fast, good at following instructions |
| Gemma 2B | `ollama pull gemma:2b` | Lightweight, lower quality |
| CodeLlama | `ollama pull codellama` | Good for shell/code analysis |
| Phi-3 Mini | `ollama pull phi3:mini` | Very fast on CPU |

---

## Security Notes

- The shell runs commands in a subprocess — it has the same privileges as your user.
- The LLM is advisory only. You remain in control of every decision.
- Logs may contain sensitive command strings — store them securely.
- The risk classifier is heuristic-based and not a security boundary. It may miss novel attack patterns.
- Never use this as your only security layer in production environments.

